2. Create a DynamoDB table
In this step, you will create an Amazon DynamoDB  table to store application data and configure the necessary IAM permissions. DynamoDB is a fully managed NoSQL database service that provides fast and predictable performance with seamless scalability. This table will store image generation data including input images, prompts, and output results.
1.Create DynamoDB Table
Search DynamoDB in the Services search bar. Select DynamoDB from the list. Then click Create table.

Configure the table settings:

Table name: ImageGenerationTable
Partition key: id (String)
Leave Sort key empty
Under Default table settings, choose Default settings to use the recommended configuration.

Click Create table.

Wait for the table status to change to Active (this may take a few minutes).

Once active, click on the table name ImageGenerationTable to view its details.
2.Create IAM Policy for DynamoDB Access
Now you need to create an IAM policy that allows your Lambda function to write data to the DynamoDB table.

Search IAM in the Services search bar. Select IAM from the list.

In the left navigation pane, click Policies.

Click Create policy.

Click the JSON tab.
{
    "Version": "2012-10-17",
    "Statement": [
        {
            "Effect": "Allow",
            "Action": [
                "dynamodb:PutItem",
                "dynamodb:UpdateItem"
            ],
            "Resource": "arn:aws:dynamodb:*:*:table/ImageGenerationTable"
        }
    ]
}


Click Next.

Enter the policy details:

Policy name: DynamoDBImageGenerationPolicy
Description: Policy to allow Lambda function to write to ImageGenerationTable
Click Create policy.



